But if it is a task with open questions or when you need to write something, in this case, I think it's better to explain it directly.

And I also agree with the statement about peer feedback. The simplest explanation is that you give feedback to someone and you receive feedback from someone. But the point is that every student should be involved in it. Otherwise, it wouldn't work. At least it's not fair if someone stays away.

As the teacher can not just give information about students' results but also give extra info about a topic or something like this, especially if he/she sees that students are interested in it.

But in the matter of fact, this course, and the idea of MOOCs in general, I like very much as an organization. Here you can go at your own pace and take time when you have the opportunity, but at the same time you get the opportunity to discuss different topics with colleagues and get a different point of view. Still, I miss the opportunity to ask questions to teachers as soon as they arise.

I also now remember that it was very interesting and useful for me when our professors encouraged us to make an annual portfolio, working on a specific task every time, the results of which we then shared in moodle and was free to discuss by our colleagues. This creates the preconditions for further discussion and thus both parties win - some receive feedback on their work, and others learn something new through the provoked discussion.

I am from Bulgaria and I am also studying at the university at the moment, a bachelor. With us, things started quite difficult - in 2020 we received only written materials in form of Word documents, as they were sent to us in 3 different places and we were given tasks on them. This was quite confusing and difficult for all students and fortunately the teachers understood it and accordingly in the winter semester of 2020 things got a little better. However, even then and to this day, several platforms are used - Moodle, Zoom, Teams, Google Meet. This makes work very difficult because you are constantly wondering "Which platform should I enter in this discipline?", but at least we already have face-to-face contact with all professors and it really helps us a lot, because we can ask questions right away when we don't understand something.

I believe that the use of platforms such as Moodle, Google Classroom, closed Facebook groups and others can very successfully accompany the traditional learning process that takes place in the classroom. For example, it has always been very useful for me when my university professors have used similar platforms and shared information about the organization of lectures before each lecture, as well as additional resources and notes from the lecture itself after it has ended.

I definitely do not think that the use of social media necessarily leads to people reading less, but I also do not agree that communication and learning on social networks can replace face-to-face communication.

I do not completely agree that punishment necessarily leads to negative consequences, but most learners are usually demotivated by punishment, so I as a teacher would not use this method in an attempt to motivate someone to learn. But there are still people who are actually mobilizing and working more focused after being punished for a similar previous act.
I like MOOCs too. And I think it's an advatage to be able to discuss topics with peers form different countries.

I think teachers can create some activities for students that they should use their devices to do them. But it shouldn't last for the whole lesson as students need to communicate face-to-face with each other and with a teacher.
I think we can leave
I, like last week, again believe that both opinions (of Mr Heineken and Mrs Wells) are too extreme and that the golden mean must be found here.

Yes, peer feedback is definitely a two-way process, because it works on the principle that everyone should get acquainted with someone else's work on a problem and evaluate it, commenting on its strengths and weaknesses and respectively receive a similar comment from a classmate - this makes the process two-sided. In addition, if a hypothetical student does not receive feedback on his or her work from the same classmate for whose work he or she gave feedback, he or she always has the opportunity to contact and discuss the person who has given feedback on his or her work additionally by personal message or conversation.

Mr. Heineken can also suggest students a range of apps for micro learning on his subject or interesting Instagram/Twitter accounts and YouTube channels. Mr. Heineken pointed out that social media makes young people lonely and less likely to socialize with their peers, while Ms. Wells' Facebook group could be a solution. Yet there are still advantages to face-to-face classes, so there is no need to completely eliminate them. Considering the above, by assigning learners pre-reading assignments and other tasks to gain the knowledge they need to participate in the class, regardless of whether the class is online, as, in the flipped classroom, we can prevent the decline in reading that Heineken is worried about, while still having an engaging class.

About the roles: I think that especially today, with the online tools, social media etc., it is important that teachers keep the role of the teacher. It can probably be tempting to shift towards the role of a friend, when communicating online and through social media, but this should be avoided.

About your question about the digital learning opportunities: I think teachers should check the OER, which are freely accessible and can bring a lot of benefit for their teaching. For example, using YouTube videos or Ted talks or other resources (for example oercommons.org)... this can save a lot of time because they don't have to create all the content by themselves and there is a lot of really good material out there which can support a lesson
